There's a repeating pattern here:

Repeated idle characters (/I/)

Start of packet (/S/)

Packet data (beginning with 55 55 55...)

End of packet (/T/)

Carrier extend (/R/)

The packet data is a bit curious, though. 0x55 is part of the ethernet frame
preamble,
but it should only appear 7 times, not... 69.

It turns out there's a simple explanation: this link is running at 100M mode,
but (Q)SGMII only runs at gigabit speeds. Rate adaption is a simple matter
of repeating each byte 10x, with the first /S/ replacing one instance of
D0:

Taking every 10th byte from the packet data, we see something very promising:
